<br>
An excellent raid overall with only a teensy bit of bitching abut loot after the event.  But wow!  What loot it was!<br>
<br>
A couple of people went down and killed the first few giants including the Warlord and the King.  However, Shaere graciously donated the Mithril Vambraces to the raid for lottoing after the event.  After a couple of teething problems with getting people down tot he raid from Lavastorm we took out the remaining giants and moved in for Naggy.<br>
<br>
The raid was slightly oversized (7 groups of high levellers, average lvl was 50) but all worked well.  The buffing went smoothly and Nagafen got killed so hard he'll be dead next time he spawns.<br>
<br>
But what about the loot?  This is what you read these things for right!  Cop a load of this!<br>
<br>
Dragon Loot<br>
<br>
Cloak of Flames    - Trewayn<br>
Cloak of Flames 2! - Kitaro<br>
Selo's Drums       - Carismann<br>
Orb of Tishan      - Frankii<br>
Bladestopper       - Castironn<br>
Heirophant's Crook - Braven<br>
Ruby               - Mellan<br>
<br>
<br>
Giant Loot         <br>
Mithril Vambraces  - Tasye<br>
Roykyl's Crystal   - Ouranos<br>
<br>
As there were no shaman on the raid (well there was but he went LD after the giants and never returned) the Crook was left as an open roll amongst all who did not win an item of dragon loot previously.  Overall this was a damned nice set of loot with 2 cloaks and something for absolutely everyone to roll on.<br>
<br>
Of course, as I said earlier, there were some complaints about my winning a cloak.  Number one was the old &quot;Bards should not roll on the cloak&quot; issue.  Well, there are other threads where we are discussing this but under my raids bards are eligible and this was announced before the raid had even left Lavastorm giving those who disagreed the opportunity to leave.  If you did not like this rule then you should NOT have come on the raid.<br>
<br>
The second is more serious.  People seemed to think that because I had reserved a dragon scale should one drop I would be automatically removing myself from all other rolls regardless.  Not only is this contrary to the loot rules I have posted up ( <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub41.ezboard.com/funitedguildsofdrinalfrm13.showMessage?topicID=34.topic">pub41.ezboard.com/funited...D=34.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> ) but it is not what was announced before the raid.  The following is an excerpt from my log file (time is in GMT).<br>
<br>
[Thu Jun 28 02:04:48 2001] You shout, 'But as raid leader I am reserving a scale and if one drops I will be removing myself from all other rolls'<br>
<br>
Please note the use of the word &quot;if&quot;.  It is a very important word in this sentence.  Certain benefits are derived from going through the torment of running these open raids.  Some leaders announce they will snaffle an item if multiples drop (so in this case another raid leader wouldn;t have even rolled on the second cloak).  Personally I prefer to just aim for my epic piece and bug out.  If a scale had dropped I would have claimed it for my epic and taken myself out of all other rolls, even for the CoF (and I would have been more than happy about it).  As one did not I was eligible to roll as a bog-standard bard as per my own loot rules announced prior to the raid.  This I did and won a random roll fair and square over 27 other people.  (Apologies to all who got a tad confused by my first joke roll.  This was a pure joke and, under the circumstances which immediately followed, people could be forgiven for thinking I had tried to use it to manipulate the loot no matter how erroneous that assumption was).  I did not &quot;claim&quot; the cloak.  It was a visible, open roll and as such it was won fair and square.<br>
<br>
Loot squabbles will always happen on open raids.  It comes with having random people come along who may not have been vetted sufficiently by the raid leader due to the open nature of the raid.  However, I try to make the workings of my raids as open as possible so as to avoid this and I take a very dim view of any participants who question rules which have been publicly announced prior to the raid.  I like to think that people actually enjoy my raids and that is the whole point of this game, to have fun.  Bitching about things of which you were in full cognisance of prior to the event is at best stupid and at worst malicious.<br>
<br>
Having said that, the majority of people DID have fun as could be gauged from the tells afterwards.  We achieved our goals and one fifth of all the people on the raid walked away with a very nice item.  As such I would say we had a damned good evening.<br>
<br>
Thanks again for coming all.  Big thanks to Balrak for helping with buffs without asking for a thing (except for a CoF.  Yeah right! 8) )  Hope to see you on the next one.  VOX MUST DIE!<br>
<br>
Trewayn Fifate<br>
